  <title>Turn on bounce keys</title>

<p>Turn on <em>bounce keys</em> to ignore key presses that are rapidly
  repeated. If you have hand tremors or a similar condition bounce keys may be useful to you</p>

  <steps>
    <item>
      <p>Press the menu button on the dock *GUI Stuff here*<p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Click on <gui>Settings</gui>.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Click <gui>Accessibility</gui> in the sidebar.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Press <gui>Typing Assist (AccessX)</gui> in the <gui>Typing</gui>
      section.</p>
    </item>
    <item>
      <p>Switch the <gui>Bounce Keys</gui> switch to on.</p>
    </item>
  </steps>

  <note style="tip">
    <title>Quickly turn bounce keys on and off</title>
    <p>You can turn bounce keys on and off by clicking the
    <link xref="a11y-icon">accessibility icon</link> on the panel and
    selecting <gui>Bounce Keys</gui>. The accessibility icon shows up if you've enabled one or more accessibility options.</p>
  </note>

  <p>Use the <gui>Acceptance delay</gui> slider to change how long bounce keys
  waits before it registers another press after you pressed the key for the
  first time. Select <gui>Beep when a key is rejected</gui> if you want the
  computer to make a sound each time it ignores a press.</p>

